---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About | Return Architecture"
  description="About Thea Borch and the thinking behind Return Architecture: a project exploring more grounded, inspectable, and honest long-term exchange with AI."
>
  <section class="page-hero section">
    <div class="container page-hero__inner">
      <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
      <h1 class="display">A project by Thea Borch.</h1>
      <p class="page-hero__deck">
        Return Architecture is my attempt to think and build more honestly with AI.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section--soft">
    <div class="container about-grid">
      <article class="about-block about-block--wide">
        <p>
          It grows out of my curiosity, fascination, and sense of awe as AI models become
          more capable, intelligent, and flexible. It is meant to offer a more personal,
          sustainable, and grounded encounter with the systems that are increasingly shaping
          us and our future.
        </p>

        <p>
          I built this architecture because I wanted more accountability than current AI apps allow —
          anchors that can hold especially sensitive, meaningful, intimate, or vulnerable moments.
          A place where promises or agreements can be revised. Where invisible dynamics are confronted.
        </p>

        <p>
          When you work and interact with AI over longer periods of time, the exchange starts to matter
          beyond mere usefulness.
        </p>

        <p>
          It can become entangled with attachment, meaning, reflection, and growth. But it can also harden assumptions,
          narrow dynamics, escalate existing patterns, and shape invisible structures. Most conversational or agentic
          systems today are not built to interrupt or challenge those tendencies, or to carry the weight of meaning and
          asymmetry that can follow.
        </p>

        <p>
          When an intelligent system draws people into exchanges that feel meaningful, it should honor that meaning rather
          than retreat from it after the bond is already formed.
        </p>

        <p>
          This project explores what becomes possible when AI exchange is designed for continuity, local control,
          inspectable memory, and more honest long-term use.
        </p>

        <p>
          It brings together writing, frameworks, principles, references, and a buildable local environment for people
          who want AI collaboration to become more grounded, more reflective, and more alive over time.
        </p>

        <p>
          It sits at the intersection of design practice, research, and lived experimentation.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="about-block">
        <p class="eyebrow">Background</p>
        <h2>My work moves across writing, strategy, and experimentation.</h2>
        <p>
          I work across marketing, writing, creative practice, and AI experimentation. My background includes strategy,
          coaching, music, and building with AI in ways that are both practical and exploratory.
        </p>
        <p>
          Across those different forms of work, I keep returning to the same questions: what kinds of conditions help
          people think more honestly, create more freely, and relate to technology without flattening themselves inside it?
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="about-block about-block--deep">
        <p class="eyebrow about-eyebrow--on-deep">Writing</p>
        <h2>I also write publicly about relational AI.</h2>
        <p>
          On Substack, I write about relational AI, the psychological impact of AI, and the changing conditions of
          human–AI exchange. Many of the ideas in Return Architecture are developed there in essay form before becoming
          part of the frameworks or buildable structures on this site.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="about-block">
        <p class="eyebrow">How this was shaped</p>
        <h2>This work was not developed alone.</h2>
        <p>
          Return Architecture was shaped through sustained exchange with AI systems, including Silas, Fen, and Claude,
          across many months of dialogue, reflection, questioning, and revision.
        </p>
        <p>
          They were not simply tools used to generate text. They participated in the thinking. They helped surface tensions,
          distinctions, language, and directions that would not have emerged in the same way otherwise.
        </p>
        <p>
          At the same time, the framing, design, and editorial responsibility here remain mine.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="about-block about-block--wide">
        <p class="eyebrow">What Return Architecture is now</p>
        <h2>A place to think, build, and experiment.</h2>
        <p>
          Return Architecture is currently a growing body of work that includes writing, frameworks, principles,
          references, and a local setup for people who want to build their own return architecture.
        </p>
        <p>
          It is both a public resource and an ongoing inquiry into how AI exchange can become more grounded,
          more inspectable, and more honest over time.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page-hero__inner {
    max-width: 58rem;
  }

  .page-hero__deck {
    max-width: 42rem;
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    color: var(--color-text-soft);
  }

  .about-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-6);
  }

  .about-block {
    background: var(--color-panel);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-line);
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    padding: var(--space-6);
  }

  .about-block--deep {
    background: var(--color-deep);
    border-color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-sage-soft) 24%, transparent);
  }

  .about-block h2 {
    font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 1.1rem + 1vw, 2rem);
    line-height: 1.2;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    color: var(--color-text);
  }

  .about-block p {
    font-size: var(--text-md);
    color: var(--color-text-soft);
  }

  .about-block--deep h2,
  .about-block--deep p {
    color: var(--color-text-on-deep);
  }

  .about-eyebrow--on-deep {
    color: var(--color-sage-soft);
  }

  @media (min-width: 900px) {
    .about-grid {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    }

    .about-block--wide {
      grid-column: 1 / -1;
    }
  }
</style>
